data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that must be replaced:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop` while loop | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Preventing rethrow so `finally` runs | Remove — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — your `Stop()` method will crash at runtime, and `ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown so your rollback logic is dead code.

---

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — OperationCanceledException doesn't auto-rethrow.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful shutdown
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
                // If GetNextItem blocks forever, it MUST be fixed to accept a token.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

## Key Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` blocks forever if it doesn't accept a token.**
This is the most critical issue. If it wraps `BlockingCollection.Take()`, use `Take(token)`. If it wraps `WaitHandle.WaitOne()`, replace with:
```csharp
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { yourEvent, token.WaitHandle });
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` replaced by `Thread.Join(timeout)`.**
The original code sleeps unconditionally then checks — `Join(timeout)` combines both into one blocking wait that returns early if the thread exits.

**3. No forced termination exists in .NET 8.**
If `GetNextItem` calls uncooperative code you can't modify, the only escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and calling `Process.Kill()`.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` broadly.**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from inner code.

**5. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.**
It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class handles this.
